            },
            {
              "type": "frame",
              "id": "cfcj0",
              "name": "Section - Apple Health",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "layout": "vertical",
              "gap": 20,
              "children": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "kTGbk",
                  "fill": "$text-primary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Method 2: Apple Health Energy",
                  "fontFamily": "Sora",
                  "fontSize": 32,
                  "fontWeight": "bold",
                  "letterSpacing": -0.5
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "UQL2n",
                  "fill": "$text-secondary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "If you don't have enough logging history for energy balance, but you wear an Apple Watch or use a device that writes energy data to Apple Health, NutriKit can use that instead.\n\nIt reads two values:\n\n• Resting energy (basal metabolic rate as measured/estimated by your device)\n• Active energy (calories burned through movement and exercise)\n\nThe sum gives your total expenditure for the day. This is less accurate than the energy balance method — device estimates have known error margins — but it's significantly better than a generic formula, because it accounts for your actual daily activity rather than a self-reported \"activity level\" dropdown.\n\nNutriKit uses a 7-day rolling average of Apple Health energy data to smooth out day-to-day variation.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.7,
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 16,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "frame",
              "id": "8X0Un",
              "name": "Section - BMR",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "layout": "vertical",
              "gap": 20,
              "children": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "3l0rS",
                  "fill": "$text-primary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Method 3: BMR Formulas",
                  "fontFamily": "Sora",
                  "fontSize": 32,
                  "fontWeight": "bold",
                  "letterSpacing": -0.5
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "lbnft",
                  "fill": "$text-secondary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "When neither energy balance data nor Apple Health energy is available, NutriKit falls back to validated BMR equations. But it doesn't just use one — it selects the best formula for your profile:\n\n• Katch-McArdle — used when lean body mass is available. This is the most accurate formula for people who know their body composition, because it bases the calculation on metabolically active tissue rather than total weight.\n\n• Mifflin-St Jeor — used when only height, weight, age, and sex are available. Widely validated and considered the most accurate general-purpose BMR equation in the research literature.\n\n• Schofield — used as a fallback for populations where Mifflin-St Jeor may be less validated (e.g., certain age ranges or when height is unavailable).\n\nThe BMR is then multiplied by an activity factor you select — from sedentary to very active — to estimate your TDEE. This is the least precise method, but it gives a reasonable starting point until better data accumulates.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.7,
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 16,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "frame",
              "id": "IX92y",
              "name": "Section - Goal",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "layout": "vertical",
              "gap": 20,
              "children": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "mcrFn",
                  "fill": "$text-primary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Goal adjustment",
                  "fontFamily": "Sora",
                  "fontSize": 32,
                  "fontWeight": "bold",
                  "letterSpacing": -0.5
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "58yRQ",
                  "fill": "$text-secondary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Once NutriKit has your maintenance calories (from whichever method), it applies your goal:\n\n• Lose weight — a caloric deficit is subtracted from your TDEE\n• Maintain — your target equals your TDEE\n• Gain weight — a caloric surplus is added to your TDEE\n\nThe size of the deficit or surplus is controlled by a slider from mild to aggressive. A mild deficit might be 250 kcal/day (~0.5 lb/week loss), while an aggressive deficit might be 750 kcal/day (~1.5 lb/week loss). The same range applies to surplus for gaining.\n\nCritically, NutriKit won't let you set a target below safe minimums. There's a floor based on your body weight and sex — the app will warn you and cap the deficit if your resulting calorie target would be dangerously low.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.7,
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 16,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
